15. EU AI ACT COMPLIANCE (Regulation (EU) 2024/1689)
    15.1 The Software is classified as an AI security tooling system. Licensee
         is responsible for determining whether their specific deployment
         constitutes a "high-risk AI system" under Annex III of the EU AI Act
         and for complying with applicable conformity assessment obligations.
    15.2 The Software's YAML rule sets and detection logic constitute "technical
         documentation" within the meaning of Article 11. Eresus Security makes
         these available to authorised licensees upon written request for
         conformity assessment purposes.
    15.3 Licensee must not use the Software as a component in any prohibited
         AI practice under Article 5, including real-time biometric
         identification in public spaces, social scoring, or subliminal
         manipulation systems.
    15.4 Licensee must maintain logs sufficient to demonstrate compliance with
         transparency and human-oversight requirements (Articles 13–14) where
         applicable to their deployment.

16. AI-SPECIFIC SECURITY OBLIGATIONS
    16.1 Licensee acknowledges that AI/LLM firewall systems process adversarial
         inputs by design. Licensee must implement defence-in-depth and must not
         rely solely on the Software as the exclusive security control for any
         AI system.
    16.2 Licensee must not use the Software to generate, refine, or test
         prompts intended to bypass safety mechanisms of AI systems they do not
         own or have explicit written authorisation to test.
    16.3 Detection rules and patterns distributed with the Software may be used
         only within the Software. Extraction of rule sets for use in competing
         products, bypass research, or adversarial red-teaming of third-party
         systems without authorisation is expressly prohibited.
    16.4 Licensee is responsible for ensuring that any AI-generated content
         processed through the Software does not constitute illegal content
         under applicable law (including CSAM, terrorist content, and
         incitement to violence under applicable directives).

